4
00:00:14,538 --> 00:00:17,839
[SPEAKER_08]: Is there any?

5
00:00:17,899 --> 00:00:18,259
[SPEAKER_11]: John?

6
00:00:19,179 --> 00:00:19,479
[SPEAKER_11]: Sorry.

7
00:00:19,779 --> 00:00:23,821
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't have them in front of me, but when I looked at them earlier, I don't think it lists me as attending.

8
00:00:24,361 --> 00:00:25,521
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

9
00:00:26,121 --> 00:00:27,642
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for noticing that.

10
00:00:28,262 --> 00:00:30,503
[SPEAKER_11]: I usually don't catch the attendance.

11
00:00:32,895 --> 00:00:33,856
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, okay.

12
00:00:34,596 --> 00:00:35,997
[SPEAKER_08]: I can, I can fix that.

13
00:00:36,378 --> 00:00:40,120
[SPEAKER_08]: So, um, with that amendment.

14
00:00:41,902 --> 00:00:42,983
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, Ron.

15
00:00:47,746 --> 00:00:50,788
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know why you can't unmute Ron because you're a co-host.

16
00:00:51,909 --> 00:00:52,289
[SPEAKER_08]: I am.

17
00:01:00,395 --> 00:01:01,036
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm sorry, guys.

18
00:01:01,056 --> 00:01:02,437
[SPEAKER_08]: We're just doing a little zoom business.

19
00:01:03,953 --> 00:01:05,434
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh yeah, there you go, you're good now.

20
00:01:05,914 --> 00:01:08,776
[SPEAKER_03]: I just heard from Phyllis too, and she said she was joining us, so.

21
00:01:09,156 --> 00:01:09,496
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

22
00:01:09,916 --> 00:01:10,757
[SPEAKER_03]: Popping on in a minute.

23
00:01:11,217 --> 00:01:12,057
[SPEAKER_08]: Good, okay.

24
00:01:13,198 --> 00:01:19,241
[SPEAKER_08]: So I will amend those, I will amend that.

25
00:01:19,921 --> 00:01:21,322
[SPEAKER_08]: Are there any other issues with the minutes?

26
00:01:24,004 --> 00:01:24,584
[SPEAKER_08]: Move approval.

27
00:01:27,205 --> 00:01:27,545
[SPEAKER_08]: Second.

28
00:01:30,127 --> 00:01:30,527
[SPEAKER_11]: Second.

29
00:01:31,207 --> 00:01:32,248
[SPEAKER_08]: Great, all in favor?

30
00:01:35,002 --> 00:01:35,723
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, great.

31
00:01:36,563 --> 00:01:50,388
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, so next is the City Council continuing of the City Council composition discussion and a provisional vote after our discussion.

32
00:01:50,428 --> 00:01:58,931
[SPEAKER_08]: So we talked a lot at the last meeting and there were some questions, a lot of thoughts.

33
00:01:59,051 --> 00:02:00,211
[SPEAKER_08]: Does anybody want to start?

34
00:02:00,471 --> 00:02:02,632
[SPEAKER_08]: Does anybody want to start?

35
00:02:10,312 --> 00:02:11,793
[SPEAKER_08]: or do people feel ready to vote already?

36
00:02:14,673 --> 00:02:33,000
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll just say, before I would vote, I would really like to have seen the interview with Patricia Brady-Doherty because I know she had some opposing thoughts.

37
00:02:34,440 --> 00:02:39,102
[SPEAKER_03]: Having been a local politician before, I would be very interested to

38
00:02:40,133 --> 00:02:45,354
[SPEAKER_03]: Here, she seems to go against the grain here and I would really like to.

39
00:02:45,975 --> 00:02:50,836
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, hear what she has to say as somebody who's, you know.

40
00:02:51,996 --> 00:02:54,857
[SPEAKER_03]: Directly been in the position where all of this would affect them.

41
00:02:55,997 --> 00:02:58,718
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, do you want to address that?

42
00:02:59,458 --> 00:03:05,741
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah, so I finally uploaded some notes from that meeting earlier today, so you can take a look.

43
00:03:06,341 --> 00:03:10,222
[SPEAKER_14]: If you have questions about more of what she said, I recorded the interview.

44
00:03:10,242 --> 00:03:16,365
[SPEAKER_14]: I promised her I would delete it and not share it with anybody, but I'm happy to go back and take another look at it before I delete it.

45
00:03:17,945 --> 00:03:20,486
[SPEAKER_14]: And I also have handwritten notes from the meeting.

46
00:03:21,467 --> 00:03:21,967
[SPEAKER_14]: In short,

47
00:03:22,952 --> 00:03:52,186
[SPEAKER_14]: her feeling on council composition was that she's against word representation because she is particularly worried about word bosses was the phrase that she used and she felt that word representation made it likely that particular city councilors would be less interested in representing the whole city and more focused on on just the word that they were elected to represent

48
00:03:54,056 --> 00:04:07,948
[SPEAKER_14]: Um, she also made a few mentions of the idea that, um, you know, uh, she was nervous about having to pay more city counselors.

49
00:04:08,869 --> 00:04:10,570
[SPEAKER_14]: Um, right.

50
00:04:10,611 --> 00:04:14,053
[SPEAKER_14]: She felt that, um, enough money was already spent on city counselors.

51
00:04:14,794 --> 00:04:19,138
[SPEAKER_14]: Uh, and I think she also mentioned a few places that the problem of

52
00:04:19,487 --> 00:04:25,931
[SPEAKER_14]: possibly like expanding the literal number of chairs for city councilors in the city council chambers.

53
00:04:26,331 --> 00:04:28,113
[SPEAKER_14]: So that was her other objection.

54
00:04:31,295 --> 00:04:31,555
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah.

55
00:04:32,675 --> 00:04:33,616
[SPEAKER_14]: That's what I have in my note.

56
00:04:34,076 --> 00:04:34,196
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

57
00:04:34,216 --> 00:04:35,978
[SPEAKER_03]: Did she define what a ward boss is?

58
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:40,600
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we chatted about it.

59
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:42,662
[SPEAKER_14]: I would have to go back to be sure.

60
00:04:43,803 --> 00:04:48,866
[SPEAKER_14]: But in short, I think I've read about ward bosses.

61
00:04:49,246 --> 00:05:05,115
[SPEAKER_14]: It's the idea of somebody using the fact that they represent and possibly have veto power over what occurs in a city ward to cement control of that ward in a way that a lot of people feel is inappropriate.

62
00:05:06,016 --> 00:05:08,597
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, thank you for that summary, David.

63
00:05:08,777 --> 00:05:12,059
[SPEAKER_08]: And these actually were questions that the Collins Center was going to help us with.

64
00:05:12,099 --> 00:05:12,800
[SPEAKER_08]: So Anthony,

65
00:05:15,451 --> 00:05:21,556
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, so I actually did this question came up about award bosses and what it means came up at the last meeting.

66
00:05:21,896 --> 00:05:25,760
[SPEAKER_12]: And so I did do a search a lot of research for this.

67
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:30,183
[SPEAKER_12]: The reason I didn't put together a paper for the, for the committee is actually for this reason.

68
00:05:30,203 --> 00:05:36,348
[SPEAKER_12]: So, there is a lot of research from historical perspective looking at word bosses in Boston.

69
00:05:37,449 --> 00:05:41,851
[SPEAKER_12]: and other communities around the United States, and particularly a lot on Chicago.

70
00:05:42,652 --> 00:05:54,317
[SPEAKER_12]: However, all the research that I found focused on ward bosses in the aldermanic system, even in Boston, and that's a system in which it's very different from a city council, even a ward city council system.

71
00:05:54,757 --> 00:05:55,558
[SPEAKER_12]: The aldermen have

72
00:05:56,938 --> 00:06:11,963
[SPEAKER_12]: more, I would say, sort of executive type authority, the authority to grant sort of permits and control that process in their particular district than would a, even a ward city councilor would.

73
00:06:13,163 --> 00:06:17,905
[SPEAKER_12]: Whereas in a city council system, or at least the ones that we have here in Massachusetts in the modern day,

74
00:06:19,067 --> 00:06:29,835
[SPEAKER_12]: the council can only act as a body, whereas under the aldermanic system, there are some things that ward counselor, ward, I'm sorry, aldermen have a little bit of individual authority over.

75
00:06:29,855 --> 00:06:31,176
[SPEAKER_12]: At least that's what I saw in the literature.

76
00:06:32,417 --> 00:06:37,481
[SPEAKER_12]: So I didn't put together a particular one, because it's not, in the modern times, it's not really focused.

77
00:06:37,501 --> 00:06:46,788
[SPEAKER_12]: It didn't really look at how the, whether ward bosses develop under a district council, ward council system.

78
00:06:48,693 --> 00:06:49,133
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

79
00:06:50,495 --> 00:06:53,517
[SPEAKER_08]: Does anybody have any other thoughts or questions about that?

80
00:06:54,318 --> 00:06:54,698
[SPEAKER_08]: Paula?

81
00:06:55,039 --> 00:07:01,264
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, I don't have nothing regarding the board bosses, but just the topic in general.

82
00:07:01,544 --> 00:07:01,705
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay.

83
00:07:03,282 --> 00:07:14,465
[SPEAKER_15]: So the stark reality is I've never been really convinced about this ward representation, though I know many people are interested in it, especially some of the people on this committee.

84
00:07:16,005 --> 00:07:19,366
[SPEAKER_15]: And I want to be swayed.

85
00:07:20,426 --> 00:07:26,848
[SPEAKER_15]: The number one argument for me is, does it increase representation of

86
00:07:28,854 --> 00:07:32,999
[SPEAKER_15]: In some way or another, does it truly reach people who we aren't reaching now?

87
00:07:34,181 --> 00:07:36,164
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'm just not sure.

88
00:07:36,184 --> 00:07:39,268
[SPEAKER_15]: I think the, you know,

89
00:07:40,557 --> 00:07:58,128
[SPEAKER_15]: having been elected as on a citywide basis, I come so deeply ingrained that my responsibility was to every citizen and certainly particularly every student in our community.

90
00:07:58,508 --> 00:08:05,052
[SPEAKER_15]: And it really went beyond student because it wasn't just often, we didn't have blinders on.

91
00:08:06,092 --> 00:08:08,373
[SPEAKER_15]: There were always things that where we,

92
00:08:09,514 --> 00:08:13,217
[SPEAKER_15]: also thought about kids who were, say, in parochial schools or whatever.

93
00:08:13,397 --> 00:08:14,798
[SPEAKER_15]: There is some interlap.

94
00:08:15,779 --> 00:08:30,070
[SPEAKER_15]: For me, that is so deeply ingrained, the thought of trying to step into, okay, now I'm going to be, and I know we're talking about city council, but I'm going to represent my ward first and then the city.

95
00:08:30,631 --> 00:08:34,033
[SPEAKER_15]: It's really hard for me to get around.

96
00:08:34,634 --> 00:08:38,256
[SPEAKER_15]: Again, if I had such a convincing argument that

97
00:08:40,432 --> 00:08:44,376
[SPEAKER_15]: we are missing a segment of our population.

98
00:08:44,416 --> 00:08:56,752
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, I think in many ways the segment of our population that we've been missing is we haven't had much representation now from our Black community.

99
00:08:56,772 --> 00:08:56,812
[SPEAKER_15]: We

100
00:08:58,254 --> 00:09:07,503
[SPEAKER_15]: Finally, Justin comes from an Asian background, but we've not had a Latino on our city council.

101
00:09:07,864 --> 00:09:16,153
[SPEAKER_15]: That's the representation that I would be wanting to try and increase, not necessarily the geographic representation.

102
00:09:17,414 --> 00:09:26,401
[SPEAKER_15]: So I'm being real honest and letting you know, I'm struggling, because I do know that there's a lot of people who think this is the answer.

103
00:09:27,202 --> 00:09:33,227
[SPEAKER_15]: Another piece of this for me is that we also have a question about balance of power.

104
00:09:33,727 --> 00:09:38,471
[SPEAKER_15]: Our current city councilors, and not only our current ones, but ones that have gone on for some time,

105
00:09:39,372 --> 00:09:48,235
[SPEAKER_15]: are frustrated in their roles because of the lack of power that they have, influence that they have on key issues or whatever.

106
00:09:48,915 --> 00:09:53,236
[SPEAKER_15]: And so I'm thinking, okay, now we're going to have more city councilors.

107
00:09:53,937 --> 00:10:01,299
[SPEAKER_15]: And, you know, when you're up there on the podium, everybody wants to get a chance to speak because it's really important to get

108
00:10:01,820 --> 00:10:05,324
[SPEAKER_15]: air time, so that your constituents know that you're doing your job.

109
00:10:06,045 --> 00:10:09,069
[SPEAKER_15]: And now we're going to have more people needing to speak.

110
00:10:10,050 --> 00:10:14,737
[SPEAKER_15]: And part of me sort of says, how effective does that become.

111
00:10:19,305 --> 00:10:23,468
[SPEAKER_15]: Is the question more how we deviate power?

112
00:10:23,828 --> 00:10:24,969
[SPEAKER_15]: Is it the number of people?

113
00:10:25,409 --> 00:10:31,013
[SPEAKER_15]: Are we going to solve a problem by creating a ward representation?

114
00:10:31,073 --> 00:10:33,435
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'm thinking ward and some at large.

115
00:10:33,895 --> 00:10:39,879
[SPEAKER_15]: Or are we going to, in fact, make it even more challenging us to operate?

116
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:43,402
[SPEAKER_15]: So those are all my dilemmas.

117
00:10:44,722 --> 00:10:45,323
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Paula.

118
00:10:48,678 --> 00:10:49,379
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, go ahead.

119
00:10:50,920 --> 00:11:04,771
[SPEAKER_10]: I will just responding to your concern Paulette around would would ward help create racial ethnic diversity in city council.

120
00:11:06,168 --> 00:11:20,599
[SPEAKER_10]: We know we have at least one war that is majority-minority, so less non-whites or more non-whites than whites.

121
00:11:20,719 --> 00:11:27,724
[SPEAKER_10]: Then the article that Milva sent out on diversity in city council,

122
00:11:30,238 --> 00:11:46,630
[SPEAKER_10]: through ward representation seem to me when I read it suggests that if you have certain some words that are majority minority then it's likely that you will increase the diversity of your city council if your city has say 30%.

123
00:11:46,670 --> 00:11:46,991
[SPEAKER_10]: quote minority.

124
00:11:50,862 --> 00:11:53,863
[SPEAKER_10]: in each board, then ward representation won't help with that.

125
00:11:54,603 --> 00:12:02,525
[SPEAKER_10]: So what we have is one ward and other wards that are getting close to being more diverse and less white.

126
00:12:02,945 --> 00:12:17,709
[SPEAKER_10]: So that's one reason I feel like I'm leaning towards board representation is I do think it would help increase the diversity of our city council based on the article that maybe the Collins Center sent to Milva

127
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:21,010
[SPEAKER_10]: and the data that we saw.

128
00:12:23,211 --> 00:12:30,714
[SPEAKER_10]: But as far as like, do you represent your ward versus do you represent this whole city?

129
00:12:30,734 --> 00:12:38,758
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know and I don't know if the Collins Center has any ways to make it clear in the charter that the

130
00:12:39,922 --> 00:12:52,933
[SPEAKER_10]: the ward representatives still have the onus of representing the needs of the city, not just their particular ward, whether that be in a preamble or something like that.

131
00:12:56,576 --> 00:12:59,418
[SPEAKER_08]: Anthony or Frank or Marilyn, do you want to answer that question?

132
00:13:00,733 --> 00:13:03,415
[SPEAKER_12]: I'll let Marilyn or Frank chime in here.

133
00:13:03,435 --> 00:13:06,697
[SPEAKER_12]: I think we can craft some language.

134
00:13:06,737 --> 00:13:16,924
[SPEAKER_12]: The one thing is that regardless of whether you're elected from a ward or from at large, you're making decisions for the city in its entirety.

135
00:13:18,705 --> 00:13:25,130
[SPEAKER_12]: When I was advising council's lawyer, that was one of the things that we always told people, but I'll let Frank or Marilyn chime in.

136
00:13:26,911 --> 00:13:27,671
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Martha.

137
00:13:28,492 --> 00:13:29,793
[SPEAKER_02]: I agree with that.

138
00:13:34,188 --> 00:13:35,409
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I do as well.

139
00:13:35,489 --> 00:13:47,813
[SPEAKER_01]: And I just from personal experience, having been a ward city councilor, I would say initially that my recollection of being sworn in is that we are sworn in to uphold the U.S.

140
00:13:48,293 --> 00:13:54,255
[SPEAKER_01]: state constitutions as well as the city charter and ordinances.

141
00:13:54,315 --> 00:14:02,278
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't get sworn in to represent any type of ward that's distinct from the other wards.

142
00:14:05,313 --> 00:14:16,259
[SPEAKER_01]: And I suspect that what you'll find is that individual ward counselors will be different.

143
00:14:16,459 --> 00:14:30,307
[SPEAKER_01]: But my experience is that most people acted in the best interest of the city while focusing on what the needs of their particular ward

144
00:14:31,077 --> 00:14:34,179
[SPEAKER_01]: may be because they are more familiar, they live in it.

145
00:14:35,299 --> 00:14:43,224
[SPEAKER_01]: They become the contact person for the people who live in their neighborhood and they represent.

146
00:14:43,244 --> 00:14:50,067
[SPEAKER_01]: I think there will be some uniqueness to each individual ward.

147
00:14:50,627 --> 00:14:52,108
[SPEAKER_01]: Counselor, should you go that route?

148
00:14:52,288 --> 00:14:56,371
[SPEAKER_01]: But the role is to serve the city.

149
00:15:01,287 --> 00:15:14,075
[SPEAKER_01]: And the goal, as I see it, is to make sure that each segment of the city, geographically, and the residents therein, have representation on the City Council.

150
00:15:14,095 --> 00:15:17,677
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

151
00:15:19,618 --> 00:15:21,459
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, David, I believe you were next.

152
00:15:22,740 --> 00:15:26,322
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah, so Paulette, I think, brought up kind of two separate points.

153
00:15:26,522 --> 00:15:30,705
[SPEAKER_14]: The first one, which was the issue of word representation, I think is one that's been

154
00:15:31,585 --> 00:15:32,765
[SPEAKER_14]: pretty well chatted about.

155
00:15:34,526 --> 00:15:47,889
[SPEAKER_14]: And last week, the thing that really struck me with that was that it seems to me that the decision of word representation is as much as anything else about how easy we want it to be to get elected, right?

156
00:15:49,309 --> 00:15:53,970
[SPEAKER_14]: It seemed to me like one of the big advantages or disadvantages, kind of, I think, depending on your point of view,

157
00:15:54,765 --> 00:16:04,541
[SPEAKER_14]: is that to be elected in a word, you need a much smaller number of votes, you need to knock on a much smaller number of doors, you need to gain the trust of a much smaller group of people.

158
00:16:06,524 --> 00:16:06,925
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think

159
00:16:08,687 --> 00:16:21,131
[SPEAKER_14]: uh, there it's, it's possible that the, that leads, in fact, I think it's likely that that leads to more diversity of a variety of different kinds on the, um, on the city council, whether that's diversity of opinion.

160
00:16:21,311 --> 00:16:33,276
[SPEAKER_14]: And we end up with people who have kind of farther right or farther left or farther in other directions, opinions or, um, more gender or, or, uh, racial diversity.

161
00:16:33,296 --> 00:16:35,356
[SPEAKER_14]: Uh, I think only time will tell, um,

162
00:16:39,113 --> 00:16:43,816
[SPEAKER_14]: I certainly imagine it will lead to more diversity of socioeconomic status.

163
00:16:43,856 --> 00:16:48,460
[SPEAKER_14]: It's a lot cheaper to run for office in a ward system.

164
00:16:50,582 --> 00:16:59,509
[SPEAKER_14]: The other one is the issue of the number of city councilors, which was one that during the interview I did struck me as odd.

165
00:16:59,529 --> 00:17:05,013
[SPEAKER_14]: Having talked to some current city councilors about the number of people on the city council,

166
00:17:07,560 --> 00:17:19,409
[SPEAKER_14]: I got the feeling that they actually felt that there were not enough city counselors and that they viewed a large part of their job as doing the kinds of things we do when we're not in these meetings, right?

167
00:17:20,550 --> 00:17:25,414
[SPEAKER_14]: Looking up reports, doing research, trying to figure out how to make the city a better place.

168
00:17:26,535 --> 00:17:35,302
[SPEAKER_14]: And I got the sense that they wished they had more people to put on more committees to think about more problems at the same time.

169
00:17:38,105 --> 00:17:47,087
[SPEAKER_14]: And I get the sense from talking to city councilors that like those city council meetings are not when they feel they're doing their job.

170
00:17:47,687 --> 00:17:58,870
[SPEAKER_14]: They feel that they're doing their job in those subcommittee meetings and when they're talking to businesses about how the rules should be changed and when they're going line by line over zoning ordinances.

171
00:17:59,910 --> 00:18:03,671
[SPEAKER_14]: And those kinds of things don't happen in the big meetings where everybody needs to get their turn to talk.

172
00:18:04,631 --> 00:18:05,052
[SPEAKER_14]: They happen

173
00:18:07,860 --> 00:18:10,041
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, at different times, so I think.

174
00:18:11,401 --> 00:18:18,123
[SPEAKER_14]: I think I, I would be in favor of expanding the city council, kind of, regardless of whether or not we choose word representation.

175
00:18:19,643 --> 00:18:24,905
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't have a strong feeling on word representation, but I think it would be a big decision 1 way or the other.

176
00:18:24,925 --> 00:18:26,786
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

177
00:18:26,846 --> 00:18:28,066
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, Daniel.

178
00:18:30,206 --> 00:18:34,690
[SPEAKER_05]: So I very similar things to say I think that yeah, yeah.

179
00:18:34,810 --> 00:18:36,311
[SPEAKER_05]: Is anybody else having trouble hearing?

180
00:18:36,371 --> 00:18:36,491
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

