00:21:24,989 --> 00:21:25,229
[SPEAKER_08]: John?

211
00:21:28,151 --> 00:21:28,451
[SPEAKER_08]: John?

212
00:21:31,393 --> 00:21:34,034
[SPEAKER_11]: Sorry, I just had a few quick points I wanted to touch on.

213
00:21:35,275 --> 00:21:38,497
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm really in favor of ward representation, so I'm just gonna hit these quick.

214
00:21:38,557 --> 00:21:39,858
[SPEAKER_11]: I hope I don't take too much time.

215
00:21:41,215 --> 00:21:46,377
[SPEAKER_11]: I think a big one, and I think it's an important one we talked about a little bit, is doing what's best for the city.

216
00:21:47,357 --> 00:21:49,038
[SPEAKER_11]: And I want to sort of flip that a little bit.

217
00:21:49,058 --> 00:21:52,679
[SPEAKER_11]: It's not just that people would be doing what's best for their ward as a potential concern.

218
00:21:52,699 --> 00:21:53,919
[SPEAKER_11]: Let's look at it now.

219
00:21:54,680 --> 00:21:59,001
[SPEAKER_11]: As we saw last meeting, we have a disproportionate representation.

220
00:21:59,521 --> 00:22:05,103
[SPEAKER_11]: More parts of our community are sending people to the at-large council, right?

221
00:22:05,603 --> 00:22:08,624
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think unintentionally for most people, and fairly,

222
00:22:08,980 --> 00:22:11,922
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm not assigning a value judgment, people bring their perspectives.

223
00:22:12,582 --> 00:22:20,347
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think it's possible that a lot of people will view what's best for the city through the lens of their experience, which will come from those particular parts of the city.

224
00:22:21,647 --> 00:22:28,291
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think worrying about ward representation, creating favoritism is a valid concern.

225
00:22:28,891 --> 00:22:36,736
[SPEAKER_11]: I also think there may be favoritism in the system we have now, because the practical reality is we're disproportionately represented by people from certain parts of the city.

226
00:22:37,890 --> 00:22:40,472
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think ward representation may be an antidote.

227
00:22:41,613 --> 00:22:42,894
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm sorry, I'm losing my voice a little bit.

228
00:22:43,234 --> 00:22:44,375
[SPEAKER_07]: That's okay.

229
00:22:44,816 --> 00:22:48,679
[SPEAKER_11]: I think the second thing I'd want to flag, and I'm from Malden where we have ward representation.

230
00:22:48,719 --> 00:22:55,764
[SPEAKER_11]: When I first moved to Medford, I was having trouble getting my trash picked up for some reason, my yard waste, excuse me.

231
00:22:55,844 --> 00:23:00,288
[SPEAKER_11]: And I didn't know who to call because we didn't have ward counselors and that's who I would call in Malden.

232
00:23:01,573 --> 00:23:06,616
[SPEAKER_11]: And so it's not just about the big votes that we think about, the budget, or the big policy things.

233
00:23:07,136 --> 00:23:09,778
[SPEAKER_11]: We're also talking about making sure city services work for people.

234
00:23:10,478 --> 00:23:13,320
[SPEAKER_11]: Constituent services are an important part of a counselor's job.

235
00:23:14,020 --> 00:23:16,081
[SPEAKER_11]: And if we have more representation, you know who to call.

236
00:23:17,462 --> 00:23:22,205
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that dovetails with the third part, which sort of ties into what Ms.

237
00:23:22,445 --> 00:23:23,145
[SPEAKER_11]: Morrison had said.

238
00:23:23,605 --> 00:23:23,745
[SPEAKER_11]: Ms.

239
00:23:23,765 --> 00:23:26,627
[SPEAKER_11]: Morrison was my religion teacher in high school, so that's how we're approaching it.

240
00:23:28,461 --> 00:23:30,802
[SPEAKER_11]: A lot of people don't know who their elected representatives are.

241
00:23:30,842 --> 00:23:34,825
[SPEAKER_11]: The United States elects way more people than most democracies.

242
00:23:35,506 --> 00:23:41,471
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think there is value, maybe a small one, but a real one, of giving people fewer people to vote for.

243
00:23:42,271 --> 00:23:50,698
[SPEAKER_11]: A ward councillor and three councillors at large is easier to have real substantive engagement and opinions about than seven councillors, 14 candidates.

244
00:23:51,538 --> 00:23:54,861
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think in that small way, it's better for democracy.

245
00:23:55,501 --> 00:23:57,643
[SPEAKER_11]: And I had a fourth point, if you'll bear with me for one second.

246
00:23:58,758 --> 00:23:59,338
[SPEAKER_11]: Oh, actually two.

247
00:23:59,998 --> 00:24:05,380
[SPEAKER_11]: Award representation seems to be fairly common across the Commonwealth in cities.

248
00:24:06,381 --> 00:24:07,421
[SPEAKER_11]: We're the outlier here.

249
00:24:08,001 --> 00:24:10,022
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think it's important to think about that.

250
00:24:10,042 --> 00:24:11,242
[SPEAKER_11]: Why is this so popular?

251
00:24:11,842 --> 00:24:27,848
[SPEAKER_11]: And dovetailing with that, the experience with Lowell a few years ago, where they had to enter into a consent decree with the federal government because they were disenfranchising people on, it might've been linguistic grounds, I think it was racial.

252
00:24:29,407 --> 00:24:34,071
[SPEAKER_11]: as someone mentioned earlier, we have one majority minority ward.

253
00:24:34,512 --> 00:24:36,694
[SPEAKER_11]: So I don't know what the likelihood of a lawsuit is.

254
00:24:37,535 --> 00:24:50,887
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't know how likelihood it is to materialize soon, but I think it's something to be mindful of that geographic distinctions are going to probably be interrelated with racial linguistic makeup.

255
00:24:51,788 --> 00:24:53,710
[SPEAKER_11]: And as a matter of representation,

256
00:24:55,067 --> 00:25:02,951
[SPEAKER_11]: as a good thing, but also in being mindful of Lowell's experience, potential federal lawsuit, I think we should account for that and make sure people are represented.

257
00:25:04,092 --> 00:25:05,233
[SPEAKER_11]: So that is all I have.

258
00:25:05,293 --> 00:25:05,573
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

259
00:25:06,393 --> 00:25:07,033
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, John.

