[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, Eunice.

306
00:29:11,382 --> 00:29:19,268
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, thanks a lot of interesting points here that I'm hearing and, you know, like the others, I'm not sold on this yet at all.

307
00:29:20,729 --> 00:29:33,098
[SPEAKER_03]: Leaning against it at the moment, but listening closely few things that, you know, I'd like to consider the expanding of the.

308
00:29:33,658 --> 00:29:38,502
[SPEAKER_03]: City council, I think would be a good discussion to have.

309
00:29:39,510 --> 00:29:53,583
[SPEAKER_03]: I think in reading through some of the responses that we got from some of our current electeds, Nicole Morrell brought that up, that she thinks the current council is too small.

310
00:29:53,803 --> 00:30:03,592
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think it was David that mentioned it earlier in his conversations with some of the electeds as well, that they wish they had more people for more committees and things.

311
00:30:05,213 --> 00:30:09,596
[SPEAKER_03]: I think Zach had some ideas about what authority or something like that.

312
00:30:10,237 --> 00:30:18,262
[SPEAKER_03]: Be interesting to see what that's all about.

313
00:30:18,282 --> 00:30:32,591
[SPEAKER_03]: Then in regards to how we're currently represented, I think Phyllis brought up the point that a lot of people don't understand how we are represented now.

314
00:30:34,684 --> 00:30:39,667
[SPEAKER_03]: And I've seen that in a lot of Facebook posts, Reddit posts, and so forth.

315
00:30:40,228 --> 00:30:46,372
[SPEAKER_03]: People coming fairly new to the city have no idea.

316
00:30:46,512 --> 00:30:51,315
[SPEAKER_03]: Like John said, I went to call my ward counselor because my trash didn't get picked up.

317
00:30:51,815 --> 00:30:53,917
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, we don't have that.

318
00:30:56,258 --> 00:31:02,923
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the biggest advantage I see toward representation

319
00:31:04,385 --> 00:31:12,992
[SPEAKER_03]: is that you're focusing on a smaller footprint, and what that seems to do is reduce the costs.

320
00:31:13,772 --> 00:31:23,139
[SPEAKER_03]: It seems like, and I think it's being put forth there by some of the candidates, that you need a minimum of $20,000 to run for office.

321
00:31:23,600 --> 00:31:24,921
[SPEAKER_03]: That's an absurd amount of money.

322
00:31:29,564 --> 00:31:32,787
[SPEAKER_03]: Without going to word representation, is there a way

323
00:31:33,733 --> 00:31:35,355
[SPEAKER_03]: to make that not be so.

324
00:31:35,375 --> 00:31:41,761
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I guess, you know, maybe some of the others can address this a bit better.

325
00:31:42,922 --> 00:31:57,557
[SPEAKER_03]: My understanding is that it's at least 10,000 or so to do a mailer, just, you know, off the top, you know, and then you've got your POM cards that, you know, get dropped off at homes or at your events.

326
00:31:58,249 --> 00:32:04,952
[SPEAKER_03]: You've got your signage and so forth and whatever other, you know, things go with running.

327
00:32:07,233 --> 00:32:27,482
[SPEAKER_03]: What I would rather see is keeping the at-large system that we have now, increasing the size of our council by making us nine or 11 maybe, and finding a way

328
00:32:28,411 --> 00:32:31,233
[SPEAKER_03]: To reduce the actual cost of running.

329
00:32:31,253 --> 00:32:37,858
[SPEAKER_03]: Maybe there are more innovative ways of campaigning out there.

330
00:32:37,878 --> 00:32:48,706
[SPEAKER_03]: I looked at, I went to city hall the other day and they're not up on the city website yet, but there will be soon.

331
00:32:48,726 --> 00:32:53,989
[SPEAKER_03]: And took a look at the campaign finance reports that the.

332
00:32:55,073 --> 00:33:01,657
[SPEAKER_03]: Candidates have to submit prior to the election, and then they submit another one in January.

333
00:33:01,677 --> 00:33:10,402
[SPEAKER_03]: And a lot of the candidates, if they get to 10,000,

334
00:33:11,898 --> 00:33:14,960
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a lot.

335
00:33:14,980 --> 00:33:21,463
[SPEAKER_03]: In the past, and I've looked at this in other years as well, some candidates don't raise any more than $4,000 or $5,000.

336
00:33:22,203 --> 00:33:36,691
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you have other candidates that seem to band together, and they're raising the heaps of money, and they're at a distinct advantage because they can do all these big glossy mailers.

337
00:33:37,471 --> 00:33:38,512
[SPEAKER_03]: I would rather see

338
00:33:39,579 --> 00:33:59,859
[SPEAKER_03]: a way of keeping what we have and finding more innovative ways for campaigning, because I think that the argument towards ward representation is that it's easier for people to campaign and cost less money, and that's where I would like to see things change.

339
00:34:02,365 --> 00:34:17,932
[SPEAKER_03]: you know, or the alternative to that would be keeping ward representation or instituting ward representation, but adding five more counselors to make us 13.

340
00:34:18,072 --> 00:34:22,513
[SPEAKER_03]: So that would be almost giving us the same amount of at-large counselors.

341
00:34:23,474 --> 00:34:25,495
[SPEAKER_03]: We'd have eight, nine, 10, 11, 12.

342
00:34:25,935 --> 00:34:30,797
[SPEAKER_03]: We'd have five instead of the seven at-large, so a little closer.

343
00:34:32,034 --> 00:34:33,695
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's my two cents.

344
00:34:34,915 --> 00:34:35,736
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Eunice.

345
00:34:37,037 --> 00:34:37,397
[SPEAKER_08]: Maury.

346
00:34:42,139 --> 00:34:42,819
[SPEAKER_08]: Can you unmute?

347
00:34:43,240 --> 00:34:43,720
[SPEAKER_08]: Let me see.

348
00:34:44,707 --> 00:34:45,768
[SPEAKER_17]: Yep, I'm unmuted.

349
00:34:46,108 --> 00:34:48,270
[SPEAKER_17]: Hi, everyone.

350
00:34:48,570 --> 00:34:56,858
[SPEAKER_17]: As everyone knows my position, I'm a proponent for the Alderman, the Ward Alderman type government has changed.

351
00:34:57,478 --> 00:35:06,966
[SPEAKER_17]: I feel as though all the years that we have done the councilors at large for city government, I think it's failed us.

352
00:35:07,647 --> 00:35:12,311
[SPEAKER_17]: And it's failed us royally when you look around the condition of the city, our type of government,

353
00:35:12,851 --> 00:35:16,935
[SPEAKER_17]: Right now, we are now chasing virtually every city and town around us.

354
00:35:16,995 --> 00:35:27,765
[SPEAKER_17]: When you should go back 25, 30 years ago, we were sitting at the top of the heap, whether it be business-wise, educationally-wise.

355
00:35:28,325 --> 00:35:30,027
[SPEAKER_17]: City council has nothing to do with schools.

356
00:35:30,407 --> 00:35:34,171
[SPEAKER_17]: To me, I think school committees should stay at large.

357
00:35:35,213 --> 00:35:39,276
[SPEAKER_17]: I, you know, it's a whole different type of government between school and city council.

358
00:35:39,837 --> 00:35:47,823
[SPEAKER_17]: But I hear the statement saying that it's going to create more diversity.

359
00:35:47,863 --> 00:35:50,405
[SPEAKER_17]: There's no guarantee who's going to run for many ward.

360
00:35:50,705 --> 00:36:00,813
[SPEAKER_17]: What I think it's going to do is attract people that are enthusiastic about getting involved in city government.

361
00:36:01,680 --> 00:36:15,924
[SPEAKER_17]: to show them that they may have more of an opportunity to get elected because they're just dealing with their area or their ward, whatever you want to call it, and go out and work that way.

362
00:36:16,344 --> 00:36:21,445
[SPEAKER_17]: I agree with what Eunice is saying, you know, to get elected here in the city, it's outrageous.

363
00:36:21,505 --> 00:36:23,765
[SPEAKER_17]: Paula, I can tell you, she's running citywide for years.

364
00:36:24,786 --> 00:36:27,266
[SPEAKER_17]: Look at this mayoral race this year.

365
00:36:27,306 --> 00:36:28,227
[SPEAKER_17]: They're around $80,000 each.

366
00:36:30,187 --> 00:36:32,969
[SPEAKER_17]: And, you know, to get elected mayor in the city.

367
00:36:33,970 --> 00:36:38,294
[SPEAKER_17]: But to me, I think it's time for a change.

368
00:36:40,315 --> 00:36:43,638
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm all in favor of voting tonight or whatever you guys want to do.

369
00:36:43,718 --> 00:36:48,102
[SPEAKER_17]: But my position still is, Ward Alderman, it's time to give it a shot.

370
00:36:48,602 --> 00:36:50,203
[SPEAKER_17]: I think this government has let us down.

371
00:36:50,824 --> 00:36:51,144
[SPEAKER_17]: Thanks.

372
00:36:51,704 --> 00:36:52,265
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks, Maury.

373
00:36:53,617 --> 00:36:58,941
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, I'm going to spend maybe 10 to 15 more minutes of discussion.

374
00:36:59,641 --> 00:37:01,542
[SPEAKER_08]: And I want to give Ron a chance to speak.

375
00:37:03,304 --> 00:37:03,984
[SPEAKER_13]: Can you hear me now?

376
00:37:04,664 --> 00:37:04,865
[SPEAKER_08]: Yep.

377
00:37:06,125 --> 00:37:16,292
[SPEAKER_13]: So first, as the unofficial chairperson of this subcommittee, I just want to thank all the people that were on the subcommittee did their real due diligence and really delve into the issue.

378
00:37:17,357 --> 00:37:20,419
[SPEAKER_13]: I want to talk a little bit about some of the things that were mentioned here.

379
00:37:21,679 --> 00:37:23,320
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, everybody had great points.

380
00:37:23,400 --> 00:37:42,170
[SPEAKER_13]: To Paulette's point about wards being, you know, favoritism, you know, I think the favoritism exists in an at-large system that we see now anyways, because there are, you know, you have your reps that you know will listen to you because you have relationships with them.

381
00:37:42,817 --> 00:37:49,904
[SPEAKER_13]: There are organizations in the city who have banded together that they have their strong relationships, and you have represented, you have some.

382
00:37:52,003 --> 00:37:55,045
[SPEAKER_13]: politicians who do their own thing no matter what the people say.

383
00:37:55,485 --> 00:37:58,266
[SPEAKER_13]: So I don't know if that changes with ward representation.

384
00:37:59,507 --> 00:38:10,753
[SPEAKER_13]: As far as the money goes, campaign money, wishful thinking, I just don't think we have the power or any method of controlling how much money you can spend.

385
00:38:11,173 --> 00:38:18,797
[SPEAKER_13]: I think if somebody can spend 20,000 and you can only afford 3,000, then you're at a disadvantage, there's no question.

386
00:38:18,857 --> 00:38:20,278
[SPEAKER_13]: I think ward representation,

387
00:38:21,038 --> 00:38:28,824
[SPEAKER_13]: The cost, just by definition, would go down because you need you know one eighth of the flyers you need one eighth of the, you know, this and that.

388
00:38:28,944 --> 00:38:31,826
[SPEAKER_13]: So, I think that's the only way we have to do that.

389
00:38:32,766 --> 00:38:38,830
[SPEAKER_13]: And, and I also hear, you know, the, the adding reps just as reps.

390
00:38:40,046 --> 00:38:46,610
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't know what research and discussion helps other than we just know that what we have would expand and we'd have more of them.

391
00:38:46,710 --> 00:38:48,211
[SPEAKER_13]: There's the pluses and minuses.

392
00:38:48,251 --> 00:38:51,033
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't think the subcommittee ignored it.

393
00:38:51,073 --> 00:38:57,617
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we just moved on because there's really not a measuring stick that says if we have seven now, we'll be better at 11.

394
00:38:59,578 --> 00:39:07,343
[SPEAKER_13]: So it's certainly an option, but I don't know if it's that kind of quantum change that we wanna make.

395
00:39:09,022 --> 00:39:24,350
[SPEAKER_13]: Finally, I'll say that I just think that we've done our due diligence, and my concern in the committee as a whole is that we have a lot of work to do.

396
00:39:25,671 --> 00:39:30,394
[SPEAKER_13]: And the decisions that we're going to make, if we make an opinion tonight, it's only an opinion.

397
00:39:31,074 --> 00:39:32,255
[SPEAKER_13]: It's just our vote.

398
00:39:32,415 --> 00:39:36,397
[SPEAKER_13]: It's going to the voters have plenty of, they've had plenty of time to comment on this.

399
00:39:36,810 --> 00:39:38,530
[SPEAKER_13]: They will have more time to comment on.

400
00:39:38,590 --> 00:39:40,011
[SPEAKER_13]: The city council will have time.

401
00:39:40,071 --> 00:39:41,991
[SPEAKER_13]: The mayor will have her opinion.

402
00:39:42,931 --> 00:39:45,752
[SPEAKER_13]: This is a living document that this is not nothing final.

403
00:39:45,772 --> 00:39:50,652
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we all have to, you know, pick it and vote on it tonight.

404
00:39:51,973 --> 00:39:52,953
[SPEAKER_13]: And we have to move on.

405
00:39:53,673 --> 00:39:58,054
[SPEAKER_13]: I think what the subcommittee proved on an aside is that subcommittees work.

406
00:39:58,974 --> 00:40:05,035
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'd like to see more subcommittees happening because you need more balls in the air to make this all work.

407
00:40:05,663 --> 00:40:12,926
[SPEAKER_13]: I mean, we can't just sit here for six months and decide on ward representation and not be talking about budget and finance.

408
00:40:12,987 --> 00:40:20,230
[SPEAKER_13]: And we're starting with the school committee subcommittee that has four or five members, and there's 11, 12 members in this group.

409
00:40:20,310 --> 00:40:27,874
[SPEAKER_13]: So there's no reason why we can't have four subcommittees going at the same time to report back and have these discussions.

410
00:40:27,914 --> 00:40:32,416
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we're missing an opportunity in the subcommittee strategy to not get more done.

411
00:40:32,856 --> 00:40:34,457
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think as I look at it,

412
00:40:35,437 --> 00:40:38,118
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, I just think the timeline just keeps going and going.

413
00:40:38,599 --> 00:40:46,422
[SPEAKER_13]: We have hardworking people who are putting in the hours, but we just haven't given them the ability to, you know, set that up.

414
00:40:46,522 --> 00:40:52,385
[SPEAKER_13]: So, and believe me, Milva has done an admirable, incredible job of organizing this group.

415
00:40:52,425 --> 00:40:53,226
[SPEAKER_13]: It's just not easy.

416
00:40:53,326 --> 00:40:55,867
[SPEAKER_13]: I know just trying to plan a meeting is not easy.

417
00:40:56,933 --> 00:41:11,587
[SPEAKER_13]: But I think we have to really take a moment to say, hey, you know, we've done our due diligence on this, we have to move the question, and we have to get the set the school committee subcommittee is going to be an enormous project.

418
00:41:12,234 --> 00:41:13,395
[SPEAKER_13]: haven't talked about budgets.

419
00:41:13,535 --> 00:41:15,316
[SPEAKER_13]: There's so many other things that have to happen.

420
00:41:15,377 --> 00:41:29,668
[SPEAKER_13]: So I'd like to really step a foot heavier on the metal on the pedal and start really moving towards having this kind of discussion times five or six so that we're talking about different things and generating more.

421
00:41:29,928 --> 00:41:33,771
[SPEAKER_13]: The conversation has been generated to wait for the survey to happen.

422
00:41:34,151 --> 00:41:35,252
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't know if that changes

423
00:41:35,768 --> 00:41:40,851
[SPEAKER_13]: the 11, 12 members of this committee in terms of where we should head.

424
00:41:41,452 --> 00:41:44,374
[SPEAKER_13]: We don't have the power to say this is the way it's going to be.

425
00:41:44,954 --> 00:41:47,756
[SPEAKER_13]: We just have a process that moves it forward.

426
00:41:47,976 --> 00:41:53,379
[SPEAKER_13]: I happen to support ward representation for one simple reason.

427
00:41:53,619 --> 00:42:00,304
[SPEAKER_13]: When you hear that as a ward in the city who has no representation over many years, that concerns me.

428
00:42:01,424 --> 00:42:02,065
[SPEAKER_13]: I think that

429
00:42:03,343 --> 00:42:13,648
[SPEAKER_13]: Ward representation will bring everybody into the process and also create new opportunities for new people who think about it but don't want to pay $20,000 to get in.

430
00:42:14,109 --> 00:42:20,212
[SPEAKER_13]: So I'll be quiet, and I'd like to listen to everybody else, then move for the vote.

431
00:42:20,512 --> 00:42:20,892
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

432
00:42:21,612 --> 00:42:22,293
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Rahm.

433
00:42:23,253 --> 00:42:24,234
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, Paulette?

434
00:42:28,776 --> 00:42:30,377
[SPEAKER_08]: Wait a minute, you're muted.

435
00:42:33,532 --> 00:42:35,074
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay.

436
00:42:35,494 --> 00:42:40,760
[SPEAKER_15]: I just want to say I really appreciate this discussion and all the points that were made.

437
00:42:41,421 --> 00:42:49,350
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that it's kind of coalesced a lot of our things that were sort of like floating around more precisely for me.

438
00:42:49,750 --> 00:42:54,035
[SPEAKER_15]: I do think that probably the strongest, I mean, without a doubt, the question is,

439
00:42:54,796 --> 00:43:00,080
[SPEAKER_15]: does it get representation for the where the wards were historically have not been represented.

440
00:43:00,801 --> 00:43:12,930
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think the other part of the discussion, which certainly is valuable for me, is the it allows more people to attempt to run because the financial burden isn't so high.

441
00:43:13,610 --> 00:43:16,212
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think those are very important and strong points.

442
00:43:16,752 --> 00:43:22,597
[SPEAKER_15]: I did want to ask what and I think Frank said he had served

443
00:43:23,290 --> 00:43:30,091
[SPEAKER_15]: Um, what happens when, uh, someone from a ward, there's, there's no candidate?

444
00:43:30,351 --> 00:43:31,092
[SPEAKER_15]: Does that happen?

445
00:43:33,112 --> 00:43:34,172
[SPEAKER_15]: And, and what happens then?

446
00:43:34,312 --> 00:43:37,953
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm just curious if anybody can address that.

447
00:43:39,833 --> 00:43:43,634
[SPEAKER_01]: Uh, I, if, if I may, it sounded like my name came up there.

448
00:43:43,674 --> 00:43:46,335
[SPEAKER_01]: So, um, I'm unaware of it happening.

449
00:43:46,595 --> 00:43:47,775
[SPEAKER_01]: I know, um,

450
00:43:49,443 --> 00:43:54,325
[SPEAKER_01]: There have been situations where there may be an announced intention not to run again.

451
00:43:54,345 --> 00:44:01,847
[SPEAKER_01]: It might take a while, depending on how long you have to pull nomination papers for somebody to pull papers.

452
00:44:02,487 --> 00:44:05,328
[SPEAKER_01]: But I'm unaware of any situation.

453
00:44:05,488 --> 00:44:07,088
[SPEAKER_01]: And I grew up in Malden.

454
00:44:07,128 --> 00:44:09,229
[SPEAKER_01]: My cousin was a city council for 24 years.

455
00:44:09,249 --> 00:44:12,470
[SPEAKER_01]: I worked 23 years in Somerville.

456
00:44:12,550 --> 00:44:13,991
[SPEAKER_01]: Been in Melrose for 30 years.

457
00:44:14,951 --> 00:44:17,192
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm generally aware of what goes on in the Commonwealth.

458
00:44:19,461 --> 00:44:28,343
[SPEAKER_01]: and I'm unaware of a situation where nobody pulled papers for a ward or enough for at large.

459
00:44:30,304 --> 00:44:45,047
[SPEAKER_15]: Was there any requirement of living in the particular ward for how long or like what prevents someone to just move into the ward just because there's an empty seat so they're going to run for it?

460
00:44:48,054 --> 00:44:50,035
[SPEAKER_01]: I would say that would be addressed in your charter.

461
00:44:50,955 --> 00:44:52,577
[SPEAKER_15]: So that would be something we'd spell out.

462
00:44:53,057 --> 00:45:00,662
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I don't know if Marilyn has a comment on that, but my recollection is there may have been something to that effect in Somerville.

463
00:45:01,643 --> 00:45:05,785
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm unaware of it in Melrose, but and I don't know about any other community.

464
00:45:05,805 --> 00:45:07,847
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, thanks.

465
00:45:09,342 --> 00:45:18,344
[SPEAKER_15]: So part of it is us putting in or defining, perhaps saying, if there's no candidate that runs from a particular ward, what happens?

466
00:45:21,405 --> 00:45:31,147
[SPEAKER_12]: Just to add on to Frank's point, I'm also unaware of, in a city of a similar size to Medford, there being no one pulling papers.

467
00:45:32,175 --> 00:45:38,218
[SPEAKER_12]: But one of the things you will be putting in the charter that the document that you're working on our vacancy provisions.

468
00:45:38,639 --> 00:45:40,059
[SPEAKER_12]: So should a seat become vacant.

469
00:45:40,399 --> 00:45:42,340
[SPEAKER_12]: What happens, there's a number of approaches.

470
00:45:43,281 --> 00:45:44,321
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm one of the ones that I've seen.

471
00:45:46,447 --> 00:45:56,213
[SPEAKER_12]: sort of when there are no candidates, is you might go to the next highest vote getter of the last election, or the body will vote to install someone for the remainder of the term.

472
00:45:56,313 --> 00:45:57,314
[SPEAKER_12]: There are a number of approaches.

473
00:45:57,354 --> 00:46:05,258
[SPEAKER_12]: All I'm saying is there's a number of approaches to deal with the vacancy, and that's one of the things this body will be looking at as it puts together a charter.

474
00:46:06,299 --> 00:46:07,019
[SPEAKER_15]: Thanks very much.

475
00:46:07,480 --> 00:46:08,360
[SPEAKER_08]: Great, thank you.

476
00:46:08,981 --> 00:46:10,742
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, last comment.

477
00:46:11,142 --> 00:46:13,283
[SPEAKER_08]: Phyllis, and then we'll go to public comment.

478
00:46:16,552 --> 00:46:21,856
[SPEAKER_04]: Paulette actually asked the same question that I wanted to ask, and I think that's pretty important.

479
00:46:22,356 --> 00:46:35,226
[SPEAKER_04]: But I do want to know that I feel really specific about this point, that if someone is going to represent the ward, I believe they should have to live in the ward.

480
00:46:35,667 --> 00:46:40,070
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know about how long all that or anything, but I think that's pretty important.

481
00:46:40,542 --> 00:46:52,984
[SPEAKER_04]: But as I just said, I think I would really prefer the ward representation because I think the person or the elected person could make themselves known better to the people of the ward.

482
00:46:53,344 --> 00:46:54,484
[SPEAKER_04]: It's a smaller area.

483
00:46:54,804 --> 00:46:57,465
[SPEAKER_04]: But my concern was, what if someone doesn't run?

484
00:46:57,605 --> 00:46:59,205
[SPEAKER_04]: What if someone doesn't pull papers?

485
00:46:59,725 --> 00:47:02,046
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that's something that may happen.

486
00:47:03,126 --> 00:47:09,027
[SPEAKER_04]: People may not have heard of it, but I find people becoming more and more disenchanted with politics

487
00:47:09,705 --> 00:47:10,545
[SPEAKER_04]: and how things run.

488
00:47:10,786 --> 00:47:13,287
[SPEAKER_04]: They just, they're not that interested in it.

489
00:47:14,447 --> 00:47:15,488
[SPEAKER_04]: That's my understanding.

490
00:47:16,268 --> 00:47:22,912
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm on a lot of committees and there's not a lot of interest in city politics or city government.

491
00:47:24,353 --> 00:47:27,854
[SPEAKER_04]: So that would be something that would be very concerning to me.

492
00:47:28,755 --> 00:47:33,377
[SPEAKER_04]: So, and the living in the ward would be critically important for me too.

493
00:47:33,517 --> 00:47:34,698
[SPEAKER_08]: So, but thanks for the time.

494
00:47:35,500 --> 00:47:35,940
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

495
00:47:36,320 --> 00:47:39,722
[SPEAKER_08]: Ron had an answer to that question, so do you want to throw that in?

496
00:47:40,023 --> 00:47:42,624
[SPEAKER_13]: Just quickly, the subcommittee did look at that option.

497
00:47:43,445 --> 00:47:52,910
[SPEAKER_13]: There are several procedures that the Collins Center has given us, even to the fact that if nobody is on the ballot, the ballot has an open slot and people can write in.

498
00:47:53,590 --> 00:47:58,013
[SPEAKER_13]: There's no option to not have a Wood candidate.

499
00:47:58,834 --> 00:48:12,751
[SPEAKER_13]: So the candidates, and that's why it doesn't really happen because you don't somebody if you find out the awards empty somebody steps up usually, but there is an option to leave an open ballot item for that ward and you would write in the vote.

500
00:48:13,231 --> 00:48:18,638
[SPEAKER_13]: Secondly, the ward representative we set the terms of whether that when the person lives there.

501
00:48:19,058 --> 00:48:24,905
[SPEAKER_13]: When a person moves out of the award there is also a procedure to replace that person.

502
00:48:25,926 --> 00:48:33,956
[SPEAKER_13]: The whole purpose of ward representation is that you live there and I would tend to doubt that someone would buy a house in Medford just to win a ward seat but

503
00:48:35,116 --> 00:48:36,437
[SPEAKER_13]: There are all kinds of rules.

504
00:48:36,517 --> 00:48:38,157
[SPEAKER_13]: We looked at it as a subcommittee.

505
00:48:38,657 --> 00:48:39,457
[SPEAKER_13]: It's detailed.

506
00:48:39,998 --> 00:48:53,081
[SPEAKER_13]: And as we didn't address it here in the presentation, only because the next process for us, once we agree which way we're going, is to work with the Collins Center to write up this article.

507
00:48:53,421 --> 00:48:55,462
[SPEAKER_13]: And that would include all those things as well.

508
00:48:57,317 --> 00:49:02,400
[SPEAKER_04]: So Rob, just as an FYI, it'd be pretty expensive seat if they wanted to buy a house in Medford.

509
00:49:02,460 --> 00:49:06,262
[SPEAKER_13]: Yeah, I don't think it's happening.

510
00:49:07,202 --> 00:49:07,662
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

511
00:49:09,003 --> 00:49:11,264
[SPEAKER_16]: But it's technically only using someone's address.

512
00:49:11,644 --> 00:49:12,665
[SPEAKER_16]: It happens all the time.

513
00:49:12,725 --> 00:49:15,166
[SPEAKER_16]: It's happening in Boston right now.

514
00:49:15,706 --> 00:49:19,288
[SPEAKER_16]: People can just use someone's address that lives in that ward.

515
00:49:19,668 --> 00:49:25,351
[SPEAKER_16]: So it is something that we should spell out in detail.

516
00:49:28,322 --> 00:49:30,264
[SPEAKER_16]: And when we do get to that point in the charter.

517
00:49:31,585 --> 00:49:33,447
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, thank you.

518
00:49:33,707 --> 00:49:35,728
[SPEAKER_08]: I want to open it up to public comment.

519
00:49:35,808 --> 00:49:41,994
[SPEAKER_08]: But first, I just wanted to see if the call in center had any thoughts about a question that has come up on the committee.

520
00:49:42,014 --> 00:49:55,725
[SPEAKER_08]: And it's also come up from some members of the public, which is the issue of the increase in cost for more for adding elected represent elected officials.

521
00:49:56,691 --> 00:49:59,936
[SPEAKER_08]: Have any other committees addressed that?

522
00:50:00,096 --> 00:50:04,905
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that, you know, is that something that, because we've been asked more than once.

523
00:50:08,968 --> 00:50:21,553
[SPEAKER_12]: I guess the only thing that I can say to it tonight is that I forget, honestly, what the salaries are for the counselor position, but I mean, just sort of nuts and bolts, you'd be adding those salaries.

524
00:50:23,093 --> 00:50:32,897
[SPEAKER_12]: You don't necessarily, I think, have to increase the staff if you don't, and that's more of an administrative decision, but you could, in theory, increase staff for counselors.

525
00:50:33,777 --> 00:50:35,178
[SPEAKER_12]: To me, it's more of a weighing of

526
00:50:36,589 --> 00:50:46,935
[SPEAKER_12]: the representational benefits that this body and the municipality as a whole finds important versus the addition of these salary costs.

527
00:50:46,955 --> 00:50:50,757
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't know if anyone else up from, my team wants to speak on it.

528
00:50:53,358 --> 00:50:54,399
[SPEAKER_01]: I would agree with Anthony.

529
00:50:55,039 --> 00:50:57,581
[SPEAKER_02]: I think one, oh, go ahead, Frank.

530
00:50:58,501 --> 00:51:01,383
[SPEAKER_01]: No, I was gonna say I agree with Anthony.

531
00:51:01,423 --> 00:51:02,564
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it's a, you know,

532
00:51:04,423 --> 00:51:23,742
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a decision that you have to make for recommendation purposes and the City Council and the Mayor will have to make as to, you know, it's an investment in your city and how valuable an investment do you see it to switch to a larger City Council.

533
00:51:24,162 --> 00:51:24,403
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

534
00:51:29,220 --> 00:51:39,004
[SPEAKER_02]: One of the issues that came up in several other communities was the cost of benefits, because some counselors were eligible for benefits.

535
00:51:40,204 --> 00:51:50,147
[SPEAKER_02]: And one response was to eliminate benefits if you were elected after the charter was adopted.

536
00:51:50,928 --> 00:51:54,529
[SPEAKER_02]: You wouldn't be eligible for the benefits that

537
00:51:58,001 --> 00:52:00,423
[SPEAKER_02]: but the other counselors were grandfathers.

538
00:52:01,304 --> 00:52:05,588
[SPEAKER_02]: But that's an issue that affects cost more than salary.

539
00:52:07,990 --> 00:52:08,350
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

540
00:52:08,370 --> 00:52:13,175
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you have one more quick comment, Eunice, before I go to public?

541
00:52:13,690 --> 00:52:20,315
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, yeah, I actually have the salaries, um, that I got from, uh, city clerk heard of these couple of months ago.

542
00:52:20,335 --> 00:52:25,178
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, the mayor makes, um, pardon me while I look at my other screen here.

543
00:52:25,659 --> 00:52:29,702
[SPEAKER_03]: The mayor makes one 35, nine 30, and this is all annually.

544
00:52:29,722 --> 00:52:33,144
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, the city councilors make 29,360.

545
00:52:33,665 --> 00:52:35,226
[SPEAKER_03]: The city council president makes 32, five 50.

546
00:52:42,151 --> 00:52:46,493
[SPEAKER_03]: and the city council vice president makes 30,640.

547
00:52:47,793 --> 00:53:01,498
[SPEAKER_03]: My understanding is that we are one of the highest paid city council groups in the state of Massachusetts, maybe behind Boston and somewhere else.

548
00:53:03,338 --> 00:53:10,241
[SPEAKER_03]: I would wonder if we are basically revamping how our government operates

549
00:53:11,637 --> 00:53:25,220
[SPEAKER_03]: is could we reduce the salaries so that they are more in line with other communities who, in some other communities, they're more along the lines of, you know, maybe 15 to 20,000.

550
00:53:26,321 --> 00:53:35,183
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, anybody who is elected from that, from X point forward, that's what they make.

551
00:53:37,179 --> 00:53:52,062
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm not sure that's in the purview of the charter, and we can look at that, but I wanted to stay on topic right now, but we can investigate whether that's something that is in the purview of the charter.

552
00:53:52,342 --> 00:53:53,243
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm not sure about that.

553
00:53:53,343 --> 00:53:54,683
[SPEAKER_08]: The call-in center probably not.

554
00:53:58,083 --> 00:54:04,085
[SPEAKER_08]: But right now, I want to move on, and we do have someone from the public who'd like to speak.

555
00:54:05,045 --> 00:54:05,285
[SPEAKER_08]: Bill.

556
00:54:06,973 --> 00:54:08,794
[SPEAKER_08]: I think I've made it so you can, there we go.

557
00:54:09,054 --> 00:54:10,015
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

558
00:54:10,375 --> 00:54:14,698
[SPEAKER_00]: Has anyone looked into like any cities that do do ward representation?

559
00:54:14,758 --> 00:54:17,059
[SPEAKER_00]: Does it actually bring out more voters?

560
00:54:17,459 --> 00:54:19,601
[SPEAKER_00]: But I would almost think it does.

561
00:54:19,641 --> 00:54:36,191
[SPEAKER_00]: And I would almost think that's a good thing where our voter turnout is very low, but maybe ward representation might bring out voters, you know, even though they're just voting for someone in their ward, but then now they can also vote for, you know, for school committees and mayors and stuff, which might actually up

562
00:54:36,642 --> 00:54:45,948
[SPEAKER_00]: up the tally of who actually comes, actually who is, you know, cause as we know, we're very low percentage in voting, but it may actually bring out voters.

563
00:54:46,008 --> 00:54:49,311
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know what Malden's percentages on voting is compared to ours.

564
00:54:49,371 --> 00:54:52,313
[SPEAKER_00]: And to Eunice's point, I think she makes a great point.

565
00:54:52,353 --> 00:55:01,139
[SPEAKER_00]: Like, and I know, like you just said, it's off topic, but just to throw my two cents in, Malden with their ward representation, they make 18,000 each.

566
00:55:01,219 --> 00:55:05,322
[SPEAKER_00]: So I would love to see it go a little lower, but again, I don't know who's,

567
00:55:06,407 --> 00:55:10,290
[SPEAKER_00]: who makes that decision or who doesn't, but that would be my recommendation as well.

568
00:55:10,310 --> 00:55:10,990
[SPEAKER_00]: So thank you.

569
00:55:11,531 --> 00:55:12,412
[SPEAKER_08]: Great, thank you.

570
00:55:13,813 --> 00:55:18,976
[SPEAKER_08]: Anthony or Frank or Marilyn, do we know anything about voter turnout and voter representation?

571
00:55:20,738 --> 00:55:31,166
[SPEAKER_12]: Not aware of any studies that specifically studied the different structures around voter representation, its impact on voter turnout.

572
00:55:31,666 --> 00:55:32,346
[SPEAKER_12]: Anecdotally,

573
00:55:35,604 --> 00:55:46,131
[SPEAKER_12]: I've been in two communities, one with Ward, one without, and the voter turnout seemed to be about the same, under 20%.

574
00:55:46,231 --> 00:55:49,253
[SPEAKER_12]: So I don't know, Marilyn or Frank?

575
00:55:54,657 --> 00:56:00,521
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't have any information or data to support one way or the other.

576
00:56:03,039 --> 00:56:07,142
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm inclined to think along the same lines as you, Anthony.

577
00:56:07,162 --> 00:56:07,963
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not sure.

578
00:56:08,303 --> 00:56:14,989
[SPEAKER_01]: We have ward representation in Melrose, and I think it's been generally below 20%.

579
00:56:16,250 --> 00:56:25,998
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of it, I think, relates to whether or not you have a contested mayor's race, and that obviously is unrelated to the composition of your city charter.

580
00:56:26,678 --> 00:56:32,183
[SPEAKER_01]: There may be situations where you have a particular head-to-head ward

581
00:56:32,992 --> 00:56:39,055
[SPEAKER_01]: Councilor race that might bring out a larger turnout for that particular award.

582
00:56:39,075 --> 00:56:43,697
[SPEAKER_01]: Um, I can think of a few examples, but that's obviously not citywide.

583
00:56:43,717 --> 00:56:46,178
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, thank you.

