01:17:14,438 --> 01:17:27,867
[SPEAKER_10]: I think some of the balance of power wasn't addressed by the memo from the Collins Center, which was around the budget, or at least I think that the fiscal balance of power is what has come up quite a bit.

887
01:17:30,188 --> 01:17:35,251
[SPEAKER_10]: And I didn't know if the Collins Center knew of any.

888
01:17:35,612 --> 01:17:37,873
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, it was addressed in there.

889
01:17:37,933 --> 01:17:42,896
[SPEAKER_08]: They mentioned that they didn't specifically cover it because it's covered by state law.

890
01:17:43,036 --> 01:17:43,617
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that correct?

891
01:17:44,550 --> 01:17:51,233
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, I would just add the caveat that one of the reasons that it's not specifically delved into is there isn't much variation.

892
01:17:51,313 --> 01:17:54,975
[SPEAKER_12]: There's Boston, which recently has this authority.

893
01:17:54,995 --> 01:18:04,740
[SPEAKER_12]: And then there is every other community in Massachusetts, which if they're a city with an elected mayor, all follow the statutory process.

894
01:18:06,265 --> 01:18:19,589
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, and the statutory process is the mayor establishes the budget, city council can either approve or decrease line items, but cannot increase or move money around.

895
01:18:19,969 --> 01:18:21,769
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that like the- Correct, correct.

896
01:18:21,849 --> 01:18:30,952
[SPEAKER_12]: And then there's a timeline that there's a clock that starts running on when the mayor submits it to when the council approves it or rejects it.

897
01:18:34,293 --> 01:18:35,613
[SPEAKER_12]: That's all covered by the statute.

898
01:18:38,245 --> 01:18:39,006
[SPEAKER_10]: And some of the.

899
01:18:39,026 --> 01:18:41,327
[SPEAKER_10]: Can I ask a question about that, Ken?

900
01:18:42,448 --> 01:18:49,372
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that dates and times of, of submissions has been an issue in Medford in the past.

901
01:18:49,792 --> 01:18:54,014
[SPEAKER_16]: Is there a way that we could kind of change those requirements?

902
01:18:54,094 --> 01:19:04,020
[SPEAKER_16]: Just say like the mayor needs to present the budget in March rather than I think sometimes you'll get presented in June and the city council would, you know, you know,

903
01:19:04,396 --> 01:19:05,177
[SPEAKER_16]: take a conniption.

904
01:19:05,317 --> 01:19:15,404
[SPEAKER_16]: You know is that something that we can address in the charter putting specifying at least dates if we can't change the actual you know the power.

905
01:19:15,444 --> 01:19:17,005
[SPEAKER_16]: Can we change the process.

906
01:19:18,521 --> 01:19:20,482
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm not, I have to pull up the statute.

907
01:19:20,502 --> 01:19:22,944
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't have it in front of me right now, but I can look at it while we talk.

908
01:19:23,004 --> 01:19:47,100
[SPEAKER_12]: But my understanding is no, what the state statute says, and Frank or Marilyn, please interrupt me if I'm misstating it, but when I say there's a timeline, there's a point in which if the mayor doesn't submit the budget at a certain point in time in the year, then he basically, or he or she, excuse me, basically gives it up and the council can sort of draft their own budget.

909
01:19:47,700 --> 01:20:05,159
[SPEAKER_12]: However, if the council, if the mayor submits it at a certain time, at the appropriate time or before that deadline, then the council has a certain period to approve or decrease the budget or do those negotiations before it has to be adopted.

910
01:20:07,880 --> 01:20:27,271
[SPEAKER_16]: I understand that, but is it, you know, I believe it's sometime in June and often, you know, what's happened in Medford is the council has wanted to be more involved in the process earlier so they could kind of have, uh, you know, the information they need to, you know, make changes and decisions.

911
01:20:27,751 --> 01:20:34,155
[SPEAKER_16]: Is there a way that we could kind of in our, in the charter kind of establish, you know, different,

912
01:20:34,694 --> 01:20:44,478
[SPEAKER_16]: dates like the mayor needs to submit it earlier or involve the council more without actually changing, you know, that, you know, interfering with that state statute.

913
01:20:45,639 --> 01:20:53,082
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, I guess my understanding and Frank, I see Frank, you can jump in after this is that, um, no, the short answer is no.

914
01:20:53,142 --> 01:20:56,844
[SPEAKER_12]: The mayor has until the time provided by the statute to submit the budget.

915
01:20:58,645 --> 01:20:58,785
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

916
01:21:00,168 --> 01:21:24,500
[SPEAKER_01]: What I have seen in cities is either by ordinance or by agreement, the mayor agrees or the mayor shall present to the city council at some point, whether it's mid-year, after the first of the year or in March, a snapshot of where the budget is at that point.

917
01:21:24,560 --> 01:21:27,462
[SPEAKER_01]: Because in effect, a budget is always just a snapshot.

918
01:21:28,923 --> 01:21:32,364
[SPEAKER_01]: you hit day two of the new budget, things are going to change.

919
01:21:32,425 --> 01:21:37,807
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, there's unpredictability, there's weather, there's, you know, building issues, there's whatever.

920
01:21:37,927 --> 01:21:47,071
[SPEAKER_01]: But so, uh, I, I don't know what the date is, but I know in Somerville, they, uh, they look to the mayor to come to them.

921
01:21:47,171 --> 01:21:50,072
[SPEAKER_01]: I believe it's in March and, um,

